segments.text: We're in the conference room at the University of Texas at Arlington.
I'm interviewing Art Anjumani, one of the faculty members here in the department.
Art, could you please clarify for me the two entities you have here in the department?
the urban studies and then the city and regional planning.
OK. We have here Institute of Urban Studies.
That is an institute mandated by the state of Texas.
and acting as sort of school.
And the city and regional planning program is, in some senses, like a division inside this sort of school that we have.
So the Institute of Urban Studies is the umbrella organization.
Inside this organization, there is a three-degree granting division or department or whatever you are calling that.
And there is also other divisions, such as research and training, et cetera.
All these are inside the Institute of Urban Studies.
City and regional planning is a sort of department, as I said, and supposedly should have been called department.
But the university, a couple of years ago, has decided that
They are not going to go with separate budget lines for the professional schools.
And they considered the institute and we inside them as professional schools, such as architecture, et cetera.
And they only gave one budget line to each one of these schools.
So the whole institute right now has only one budget line.
And because of that, we cannot have separate departments inside such schools, such as Institute of Urban Studies.
Therefore, that's why we call City Energy on the Planet as a program.
And we have other degree granting, which is urban and regional affairs program.
And we have also a PhD in administration.
These are the three degrees that we have right now in the society.
It's a PhD in urban administration?
No, PhD in administration.
It's only administration.
Planned administration.
And we are sharing that with business school.
I see.
You don't have a PhD in?
a planning-related topic.
No, we don't have direct PhD in planning-related topics.
Inside that PhD in administration, there is a major in city and regional planning, which is relatively small major, rather than they have something above major as a primary or something.
I don't remember what's the name.
But one inside that Ph.D. program, basically getting Ph.D. in administration, can have a major in city and regional planning, which is not equivalent to Ph.D. in planning at all.
It would be more or less an emphasis.
It is like emphasis.
How long has the...
city and regional planning program been in existence?
Do you know when it was created?
Those I'll need to go back to our, you know, books and our things.
I came here at 1979 and I believe at that time the program was in existence perhaps for
I would say for six years then.
I'm not sure exactly when.
Joel would be a better person to know exact date because he was one of the people that basically put the program together.
He was hard, I think, to do that.
All right.
How many students...
do you normally enroll approximately every year?
You know that in planning programs, normally these things go up and down.
And especially in this program, since my being here, we have been always in different situations depending on what was going on.
Overall, up to a couple of years ago, we were somewhere between 20 to 30 students going back and forth.
In the last two years, our enrollment drastically has increased.
Right now we have quite drastically, of course I mean in terms of our small program.
We have about 40 students.
I think we have about 44, 42, something like that.
And perhaps for next year, we're going to be about 40 some.
But after that, no one knows.
You know that planning programs overall, you're losing students.
So I would think that at the most, we're going to stay in 40.
Or perhaps we're going to go back to 20-some that we were one time before.
Looking at your program here, what would you characterize as its major emphasis?
How do you feel that it can be identified?
What sort of planning program do you have?
I would approach that in this way, that at the beginning when I was here, we had a program which basically trained generalized type of, generalist type of planning.
And we had that for several years, and even though we were encouraging the students to sort of specialize,
both because of the structure of the program and perhaps also because of the expertise of the faculty.
It seems to me it was difficult to specialize at those years.
Then a couple of years ago we went through a major effort to revise the program.
And as revision, we changed the number of units required.
Basically, right now, we are requiring 48 credit hours.
And as part of that, we try to bring the program out of generalist approach and explicitly encourage students to specialize.
And according to resources of our faculty, by that I mean the areas that they are involved and they can teach, et cetera,

We came up with a scheme which is sort of Chinese menu type scheme and people can mix and match the courses and the areas but basically we offer three major areas of specialization which inside each one of those there are focus areas of specialization.
Those three areas are first land related things.
We call that land development scheme.
and inside of this there are land use planning, urban design, real estate development or whatever you can think that is related to physical planning and especially land.
It is inside this one.
The second one is sort of socio-economic type of planning and again inside of that there are different specializations such as housing or policy oriented transportation etc.
And third one is more number crunching, computer-oriented analysis, heavy quantitative analysis type of specialization.
And then, of course, we allow that students can even mix and match with these things.

For example, if someone going to land use planning may like to have a good knowledge of computers, so they're going to take a couple of the computer-related ones and some of the hardcore of land use development or whatever.
But basically this is all we have.
I see.
Do you have what?
might be regarded as a core curriculum of minimum courses that everyone...
Yes, we have inside this program, we have a core area or core courses, which I believe are about 41 hours.
As I promised, I'm going to give you the summary of the program, basically.
There are about 21 hours or 24 hours of the core courses, which... About half.
So it is 21.
This is a little less than that.
A little less, yeah.
And inside that, we also have two project lab or laboratory, which is normally required, but some programs may not put inside the core areas.
They are put directly in core area.
So if you reduce that, so it would be six minus 21 would be 15 hour of core courses, then two project labs.
and then every specialization area that one is selecting to go in would be five courses or 15 hours required two of those five courses are required which is mandated what courses they are
And three would be elected on the basis of the sub-area of specialization, that focus area of sub-specialization that I said, which would be selected by the advisor and the students design.
And then I believe we have about 12 hours of electives, depending on if they are doing thesis or exam or whatever.
Because if they go thesis route, they have to spend some of those for their thesis.
Otherwise, if they are doing comprehensive exam, the whole 12 hours is open for electives.
The electives, we heavily encourage the students to use those also for specialization.

So hopefully four courses there and five courses there, so nine courses we try to use for specialization, the students to basically get some knowledge of the area that they think they are specializing.
Do you require an internship?
Yes, we require internship, but students don't get credit for registering for internship.
That was one of the means that we reduced our logs.
We give them one credit hour.
One credit hour.
That's not a bad idea.
We never thought of that.
Otherwise, perhaps we would have done it.
There was a big debate about it, and it varied substantially depending upon the student's committee chairman in the past.

And it was so flexible that it created some problems among the students, because some would say, well, I worked all summer and I only got one credit hour, and another worked six weeks and he or she got three.
And so we decided everybody should get one.
Yours is semester system or quarter?
Semester.
Semester.
We've always been semester.
You're on semester.
Yeah, we are semester too.
Okay.
Your general perception of planning education in Texas, what role do you see UT Arlington's efforts taking with respect to the statewide view of planning education?
I would admit that I am not that much familiar with the other two programs, your program and also us in program.

I know overall that these two programs are there and I know some of the faculties like you and I have seen their curriculum before but right now I don't really know that what are the difference between the programs.
I would say our program

in comparison to some of the national programs that I know, is perhaps a little more oriented toward practice of planning than upon their type of theories or philosophical discussions or something of that nature.
And I personally like it to be that way.
I always consider planning as a profession.
I guess all of us consider planning as a profession.
And I like to see that, like any professional schools, we are training our students to come out as actual planners and to use what they have learned at schools.
Of course, as you know, planning hasn't been developed as much as, say, engineering or civil engineering or something.
So we are attempting to do that, but we have limitations in doing that.
And of course, because of that, perhaps, and also educational type of philosophies,
there would be always theoretical courses such as planning theory or those type of things around, and we have those.
But I overall see that our programs, in comparison to some of the programs that I've seen up in North or in the West Coast, is more geared toward actual applied planning.
And I think that's what we need in Texas, in my view, because
Nothing much has been done in Texas, planning relatively new in comparison to the rest of the nation in Texas.
Therefore, we need people to come out of these schools and go and apply things.
But on the other hand, one thinking that way may be sort of misled to think that if we are saying apply, we necessarily talk about

applied planning in city which normally end up to be land use related those type of things of course that to me is sort of core of planning on the other hand there are lots of other aspects of planning that we try also to bring them about and
those would be applied, maybe eventually end up as policy analysis or something for a department or even a private organization.
But I meant mostly to have some application to discussions that we are having in class or whatever.
There seems to be almost an untapped resource for planners in corporate planning.
and corporate affairs and what many of their job descriptions call for can be termed planning.
But they don't call it that because they're not
they're coming at it from a different perspective.
In fact, up to a year or a year and a half ago, the growth was a big thing in Texas, especially real estate growth was a big thing here.
We had lots of applicants that they were coming here that their aim wasn't to go and work in public agencies at all.
They were planning to come and get the degree and go to a

private sector, and mostly they wanted to go to real estate development, either in business for themselves, or they wanted to be hard first with the real estate development firms and eventually go for themselves also.
Perhaps now it has been to reduce those type of people, but I see real demand outside the people.
And some of these, incidentally, they had degrees, MBA degrees even.
business degrees, and they realize that what they need they have to learn in those type of environments.
And that perhaps is true in your program.
I don't know if you had similar experiences.
Well, we did.
And we created a new degree, the MSLD, Master of Science in Land Development.
And it was the right program at the wrong time.
About the time it got started, the bottom fell out of the construction industry.
so that enrollment has fallen off perceptibly every semester.
And it's a good program, but it just simply consumed, I think, an inordinate amount of time of our faculty and our resources at a time when we should have been bolstering the MUP degree.
What's the MUP degree?
The Master of Urban Planning.
Oh, OK.
Yours is a Master of City and Regional Planning?
City and Regional Planning.
MCRP.
MCRP.
Yeah.
So, let's see, you offer the PhD and the dissertation, the MCRP, and what other degree?
Well, what we call it, ORBA, it is Urban and Regional Affairs.
Urban, what is it, a Bachelor's or Master's?
Master's.
It's MA degree in Urban and Regional Affairs.
Basically, Urban Affairs program.
Uh-huh.
Well, a lot of affairs are urban.
Yeah, but I guess rather than saying it's basically an urban affair program, I should have said that it basically is getting closer to public administration side of the issues.
I see.
We may in future try to get a public administration degree or so.
I don't know.
But we don't have such a degree.
So this, I think, is some sort of substitute.
People who are going to work in the urban environment, but not necessarily interested in the planning side of it.
I am not that familiar with the program, so I can't give you more information.
But my understanding is that there is good differences between that program and our program.
In your MCRP degree program, what is your faculty-student ratio?
Of course, since we said the student number were changing very quickly almost, I would think that the faculty-student ratio also would change very quickly.
Basically, we have...
I don't know, the faculty members are a little loose here.
Three people, 100%, I can see that they're always involved in teaching and everything of planning.
Then in addition to those, we have Bob Wagner, who also teach in planning all the time.
In addition to those, also, as you know, he does that, what's that, the newsletter for Texas planners.
He's editor of that, and recently you all given that Texas planner thing to him, too.
So he's another faculty member always there.
We have Paul Guizzo.
supposedly sort of half-and-half with us.
We have another faculty of that nature.
I don't know if you have met him or not.
Jim Corneil.
He is also supposedly half-and-half with us.
What's his other half?
The Orba and Ph.D. programs.
These are all people that I'm talking right now are in the institute.
Then we have Andrew Seidel.
who is a person with, I believe his bachelor's degree is architecture, if I am right.
But he has a master's in city and regional planning from Harvard.
And then he has a PhD in planning from, I believe, Michigan.
So he is a planner, and he teaches planning type of courses.
And his situation with us is sort of vague.
Supposedly, he should be with us.
I mean, name-wise and teaching-wise, et cetera.
But he was hired before our move from architecture to here by the Orbaugh program and the PhD program.
So officially, he was hired with them.
But right now that we are here, he's also with us.
So he's also editor of the Journal of Architecture and Planning Research.
So he is, again, an our faculty member, in my mind, can be easily 100% planning.
But he happened to be at least officially under other
So we are dealing with that.
We are trying to bring him basically to our program as much as we can.
And he teaches planning-related courses.
He teaches urban design courses.
Urban design is one of his specialty.
And he teaches urban geography and introduction to planning and those type of things.
But some of these courses before our move to here has been part of their programs.
So those courses attract the students both from our program and also from their programs.
When you say their, you're talking about...
I am talking about that urban affair program that time.
So they had those type of courses prior to movement of city and regional planning out of architecture to here.
They had those courses.
And it was hard to teach those courses.
That's why he was here.
I see.
the structure is a little bit complex.
Yeah, it is.
And, you know, we have also gone through a major change in the last two, three years.
As I said, the university changed their attitude about the professional schools.
And we had another major big program inside the institute.
The institute, for some reason, I don't know the detail, decided that they don't want that program inside the institute.
That was criminal justice program.

and at least for now that has gone out of the institute to other I believe it's in liberal arts or somewhere so when they moved out then the that caused when you are overall small organization when a major part goes out the relationship between others also gonna change and we are in that mood of change now we are changing constantly and
I think we are opening up more to each other.
I'm seeing as a trend inside our organization that we open up our courses to their students.
They open up their courses to us.
Our faculty to teach also for them, their faculty to teach for us.
In fact, we have had good faculty inside their faculty that perfectly would have fit in my mind.
I'm saying my personal ideas.
In my mind, some of their courses would have been excellent for our students.
Like, for example, we had the cost-benefit course.
I think that's exactly a course we need.
Then we have there... By we have, I mean in those programs.
We have public finance courses, which are traditionally being taught in planning programs.
And those are being taught in those two programs.
So we have lots of courses like that.
And then we have statistic courses that we teach here that can go also to be taught there.
And all those type of things that we've got to work it out to basically improve the quality for students.
for also the faculty to be able to be involved in all of these.
Strangely enough, as I was telling you, I teach a statistics course here in the planning program.
And as you know, my background and education has been first in architecture.
In fact, I have been a practicing architect for 10, 15 years before even starting my planning education.
Where did you get your degree in architecture?
Back home.
I got a master's degree in architecture back in University of Tehran.
Did you study with Dr. Mozayeni?
No, Mozayeni came to teach there when I was almost at the, you know, doing the final thesis and all things.
You might have known Tabibian.
Yeah, Tabibian was just two years ahead of me in the architecture program.
I see.
Then I was also, when I was practicing architects back in Iran, Tabibian and I were both in a
supposedly some sort of doctorate program in planning that they had there.
And he was, again, a year or two ahead of me.
And he got a special scholarship from them.
And he went, I forgot, to Eastern Europe or somewhere.
to get a degree from there.
I forgot where.
He got some sort of degree and came back and started to teach there, I heard.
I think he was in the United States, too.
Was he?
I don't know.
I've forgotten exactly.
So in any event... We have that in common, then, because I was a Fulbright assignment to the University of Tehran for the fall of 1978.
Yeah, you told me that it's such a bad year that all the revolutions start.
Yeah, bad timing.
Bad timing.
But in my case, I never finalized that degree.
In fact, I don't believe that that degree program stayed there, that PhD type of program that they had.
And I was basically, I was a little dissatisfied with what I was learning, so I quit that.
I was practicing architecture until 1974 that I came here.
I immigrated in 1974.
I didn't come to go to school here.
I basically came as an architect to work.
And my wife basically pushed me to go to planning school.
I wanted to go to urban design program in either UCLA or USC.
Did you move to California?
Yeah, we moved to California.
I had a friend there at UCLA.
And he had gone to an urban design program there.
I don't know urban design or architecture, whatever, but they sort of specialized in urban design.
And my wife sort of pushed me.
She was also an architect from the University of Tehran.
She is an architect from the University of Tehran.
She wouldn't be allowed to go to school right now.
Yeah, right now, I don't know.
Is that true?
In any event, we end up in planning program.
I was just telling you that I am coming from heavy design background.
I was basically designer.
Even in the architect offices, I normally acted as a designer.
I wasn't a working drawing type of man.
And then I got a little fascination with the quantitative application of planning.
That's why I shifted my education there.
And when I came here, they basically hired me to teach mostly quantitative courses.
And I started to teach statisticals.
And I have my beliefs that I think it is perhaps better if someone can teach statistics and especially other non-statistical quantitative methods.

to planning students if he himself is a planner and I have my reasons and I don't want to take your time going to all those details, but basically statistics by itself is very dry and boring material and if you go to statistician to teach those things to you they're gonna go to such a length of materials that
that I would say 95% of the things won't be things that you actually would need if you become an applied planner.
And I can say that bravely because I have taught that course now for eight, nine years.
And from the beginning, I started to copy the course that I had with my teacher back when I was in the planning programs.
And that person even was semi-planner.
what I realized with these years of teaching that so many materials are really

excessive we don't need those we don't need all those proofs we don't need all those talking about so many details we only need to know what's the concept and how that can be applied i don't mean that my course by now is perfect course i still you know revising and every day i'm changing realizing more and more that what really at least in our program our students are not going to go
mostly to PhD program or if they go they have to take an R-statistic course.

So basically we are teaching these things to these students to go outside and if ever they needed to apply something of statistical nature to remember those and to have some concepts what's the whole thing about.
And I think this view would change what you are teaching to them.
That's why I think that would be better overall if a planner
with experience in planning, and especially to experience a little in the physical side of it, to teach them statistics.
Of course, it would be difficult to find such a rare combination, and I guess I'm one of the rare ones.
But I don't think that students love my course.
They don't like my course either.
Statistics is...
Strange topic, you know.
Some people are good and they would like it.
Some people have difficulty of understanding what is this whole thing about and what's the application of it.
Some students may think at the end of any statistical course, so what?

We know all these techniques, what we can do with those, especially students coming from architecture school, et cetera, that they have learned to have something, and they sit down and come up with a product, which is a finished and meaningful product.
And I think it would be difficult to tell them what they are, unless that you are also understanding where they are coming from and what they are saying to you.
Just a view of the statistics I talked about.
But let me complete that if we have time.
Let's see how our tape is doing here.
This is the other course that we have in our program.
We call that method course.
And that's non-statistical, but mostly quantitative type of planning-related methods.
I really think that that is more important than statistics to planners.
And it is good if someone, an actual planner,
teaches those courses rather than a scientist or something.
What sort of methods do you include?
In that one, I teach also that course.
I have about five, six, seven basic topics inside.
One is basically land use models.
And I think the importance of the land use models, which is mostly mathematical models, is not really that they're going to go and apply those models because it might be difficult for them.
But I think conceptually it is very important that they know how scientifically they can view the urban area and analyze the structure of urban area and know what's causing what.
